    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, can you help me understand the difference between a \"confidentiality period\" and a \"survival clause\" in a standard contract? I'm trying to make sure I don't miss anything important.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A confidentiality period and a survival clause are two distinct concepts in contracts. A confidentiality period, also known as a non-disclosure agreement (NDA), is a provision that restricts the use of confidential information by a party during a specified period. It's like a protective shield around sensitive data, ensuring it doesn't fall into the wrong hands. \n\nA survival clause, on the other hand, is a provision that continues to bind parties to a contract even after the contract itself has expired or terminated. It's like a lingering presence, ensuring that obligations and responsibilities remain in effect, even if the contract is no longer in force. \n\nThink of it this way: a confidentiality period is like a temporary ban on talking about a secret, while a survival clause is like a permanent obligation to keep a promise. \n\nIn a standard contract, you might find both provisions, which can be crucial in maintaining confidentiality and ensuring long-term commitments. It's essential to carefully review your contract to understand the specifics of each clause and how they interact with each other.",
      "source": "target",
